## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has **three** patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | Problem on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires — the exception is never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop via the token.
                // Loop condition will exit naturally on next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in modern .NET.
            // If this fires, GetNextItem/ProcessItem must be fixed
            // to check the token more frequently.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitOne`, `Task.Delay`, async I/O) — a bool cannot unblock a waiting thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of preemptive kill |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No auto-rethrow with cooperative cancellation — loop condition handles exit |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping blindly |

### Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Cooperate

Your comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." This is the **#1 migration risk**. If it blocks on a synchronous call that ignores the token, `Cancel()` won't unblock it and `Stop()` will hang.

Fix depends on what it blocks on:

```csharp
// If it blocks on a BlockingCollection<T>:
var item = _queue.Take(token);  // wakes immediately on cancel

// If it blocks on a WaitHandle/ManualResetEvent:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });

// If it blocks on Thread.Sleep:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollInterval);  // replaces Thread.Sleep

// If it blocks on synchronous I/O (socket/stream):
// Switch to async overload:
var item = await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, token);
```

### Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` references remain
- ✅ No `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks remain
- ✅ No `Thread.ResetAbort` calls remain
- ✅ Rollback cleanup logic preserved in `OperationCanceledException` catch
- ✅ `FlushBuffers()` still runs in `finally`
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed via `IDisposable`
- ⚠️ **You must update `GetNextItem()` and `ProcessItem()` to accept and check the `CancellationToken`** — otherwise cancellation won't be timely
